<span class="displaytext"><b><em>insists he was right to vote against bush tax cuts</em></b> <p><b>nbc's tim russert: <em>"do you believe that voting against the bush tax cuts was a mistake?"</em></b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate full): <em>"of course not."</em></b> (nbc's "meet the press," 1/6/08) </p><p align="center"> <em>watch sen. (candidate last) oppose tax relief here:</em> <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5swpjxmnu-a">www.youtube.com/watch?v=5swpjxmnu-a</a> </p><p><b> <u>sen. (candidate last) is still glad he voted against real tax relief for working families:</u> </b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) still believes he was right to vote against numerous (PARTY NAME) tax cuts.</b> nbc's tim russert: "do you believe that voting against the bush tax cuts was a mistake?" sen. (candidate full): "of course not." (nbc's "meet the press," 1/6/08; www.youtube.com/watch?v=5swpjxmnu-a) </p><p><b> <u>sen. (candidate last) voted against the 2001 and 2003 bush tax cuts:</u> </b> </p><p><b>in 2001, (candidate last) was one of only two (PARTY NAME)s to vote against the $1.35 trillion tax cut.</b> (h.r. 1836, cq vote #170: adopted 58-33: r 46-2; d 12-31; i 0-0, 5/26/01, (candidate last) voted nay) </p><p><b>in 2003, (candidate last) was one of only three (PARTY NAME)s to twice vote against the $350 billion tax cut.</b> (h.r. 2, cq vote #179: passed 51-49: r 48-3; d 3-45; i 0-1, 5/15/03, (candidate last) voted nay; h.r. 2, cq vote #196: adopted 50-50: r 48-3; d 2-46; i 0-1, 5/23/03, (candidate last) voted nay) </p><p><b> <u>sen. (candidate last) voted against real tax relief for new hampshire families:</u> </b> </p><p><b>in 2004, the u.s. treasury estimated the effect of the tax cuts sen. (candidate last) voted against on new hampshire:</b> </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p>- 525,000 new hampshire taxpayers would see "lower income tax bills" because of the tax cuts (candidate last) voted against. </p><p>- 125,000 business taxpayers in new hampshire saw tax relief which they could invest in "new equipment, hire additional workers, and increase pay" due to the tax cuts (candidate last) voted against. </p><p>- "more than 480,000 taxpayers in new hampshire will benefit from the new 10-percent bracket enacted" because of the tax cuts (candidate last) voted against. </p><p>- "nearly 140,000 taxpayers in new hampshire will benefit from the ... reduction in income tax rates above 15-percent" because of the tax cuts (candidate last) voted against. </p><p>- "more than 180,000 married couples in new hampshire will benefit from" elimination of the marriage penalty, which (candidate last) voted against. </p><p>- "more than 125,000 married couples and single parents in new hampshire benefit from the increase in the child tax credit" that (candidate last) voted against. </p><p>- "125,000 taxpayers in new hampshire will benefit from the reduced tax rates on capital gains and corporate dividends" that (candidate last) voted against. </p><p>(<a href="/opencms/opencms/news/press-releases/www.treas.gov/press/releases/docs/states/newhampshire.pdf">u.s. treasury department website</a>, posted 4/1/04) </p></blockquote></span>



